reviews_data.review_text:
I mistakenly thought this was a coffee shop, and it's a restaurant, so that's on me. I had a breakfast muffin, which was very good. I was disappointed by their hot tea selection, which was basically Bigelow tea bags for the price of a box of tea at the grocery store.

The staff was super nice. The presentation of food was lovely. The environment was very cool. It's all high top tables inside, and a few tables outside  The music was loud inside, so it wasn't that conducive to conversation. My group was able to get a table outside, which was nice. The patio is adjacent to the parking lot, so cars are driving by, etc. it's very shaded, so that was nice in the summer.

I'd return if someone invited me, but I wasn't so impressed that I would make it a priority to go back. There were a lot of people there the morning I went, which shows that plenty of others really enjoy this place.

You order at the register so we went with a Bananas Foster Latte and Crème Brulee Latte to drink.  Both of those were top notch!  For food, we ordered Avocado Toast, Breakfast Burrito and the BELT. reviews_data.review_text: If you're looking for a nice café where you can do some computer work, DON'T COME HERE. They only want customers who come in, spend money, and leave quickly. reviews_data.review_text:
Food is good here, but I was disappointed with the way they treated me and my golden retriever.  There are no servers to sit you outside, you get a number after you order FROM A COUNTER and go find a spot, which would make anyone think its first come first serve. Also, keep in mind, I did see a small sign on the door about not bringing dogs inside (other than this, no other signs insight), so I do the natural thing and tie her up to the open table outside I plan to sit at.  When I did this and went inside to order, some couple tried to go over to that table to sit and looked like they saw a ghost when they saw the table they "planned to sit at" was taken by a golden retriever...

One of the workers saw this disheveled couple, knew that it was my dog cause she watched me do it, came over to me in line and got upset with me and started claiming they have "signs EVERYWHERE" (ref. the 3rd sentence) stating it not being first come first serve... When I denied seeing any sign anywhere stating that, I responded with "this is a coffee shop, what do you mean I can't tie my dog up outside then order from the COUNTER inside", she followed up with "You don't have to eat here" so I took her up on that suggestion and left.

The tone and handling of the situation were unnecessary and left a very negative impression. It's unfortunate, because the setting and food are otherwise enjoyable. I hope the management considers providing clearer signage and a more respectful approach to customer service in the future.
reviews_data.owner_answer:
Hi Kevin, 

We're sorry to hear you didn't have a great experience! Our tables are first come first serve and we ask that you order before you sit or claim a table. If you have any questions in the future, please do not hesitate to ask our staff onsite or reach out to us on social media! We're always willing to help clear up any confusion. We know it can be hectic on the weekends and hard to find a spot, especially with a pup in tow, but we're always here to help in any way we can.

My food had to be warmed up when I got home, and my drink got cold while I waited for my food to arrive. I saw other people get served before me, and I had to ask when they planned on bringing me my meal.

Then when I asked, the woman said, “Oh, are you number 4?” I said yes, and she went to get my food. Like, how long did you just let my food sit in the kitchen? How did you not even consider me when you could see me sitting there IN THE MIDDLE OF THE RESTAURANT? How could you go 30 minutes without even saying anything to a guest who clearly isn’t eating yet?

I am so humiliated, and even more upset that I paid for such a terrible experience. This is my first and LAST time patronizing your business.

All I can say is the lady cleaning off the tables made me NEVER want to return again. I was told by one waitress that you had to order then you could sit down at table. Okay....cool! My friend and me ordered...found a table, sat down. Not a problem. Then I noticed another table being cleaned off.....so I asked my friend to move to this other table with me.  As I was about to sit down....the waitress that cleaned the table told me we couldn't sit there. The reason she said we couldn't sit there is because the cashier taking the orders was about to sit people there...! Wow! She lied to me in my face! She balantly lied to me in my face!!!! If the 1st waitress said you order first then sit down....why did the waitress cleaning table say something totally different? She lied! There was even a sign that said you order 1st then find table. It said nothing about cashier finding a table for us. Wow! Another table overheard  the waitress cleaning the table say this to us and knew the waitress was lying 🤥!  This is not the type of business establishment I will ever go back too!

All I can say is....if you lie to me to my face....you truly don't want me to come back!

Your TEAM knew exactly what they did. The second waitress lied. Plan and simple.  The team should be on the same page.  Does that make sense? Your establishment has the business it wants...and it's not me. The couple that overheard the waitress lie...said they will not be back either.

It disheartening that I experienced this...and I'm being blamed for your employee lying too me.
reviews_data.owner_answer:
Hi Stacey, 

We're sorry you did not have a great experience. Our service is quite different than the usual Cafe. Our team's goal will always be to make room for anyone who walks in the door. Our team tries to anticipate open tables to help people find seats but it's a little harder to track if guests start playing musical chairs. So, both teammates were correct - you must order before you take a seat but if our team sees an open table, we will do our best to get you seated. Does that make sense? 

Within our little Cafe we've created a community that is incredible flexible and open to sharing seats + eating with new friends which we're very grateful for! Next time, we encourage you to ask for a manager to clear things up to avoid any ill feelings - we always appreciate the opportunity to discuss things in person. 

Have a great day!

MOLDY FOOD

My son and I visited ROOTS today for the first time. We ordered breakfast sandwiches, grits, and a blueberry muffin from their case. The hot good was tasty, the ambiance lovely, and overall good atmosphere.

However, the muffin we received was molded. We took it to go and didn't notice it until later. My son took a bite of the muffin he complained he didn't like it and tasted funny. Upon examining it I found mold spots all on the inside of it....

I really wanted to like this spot, however this was disappointing.

Very nice neighborhood cafe.

1.  The coffee is  reasonably priced and taste great.  My wife ordered a latte and enjoyed it so much she grabbed another to take home.

2.  The breakfast sandwiches taste great but are a little overpriced.  We ordered turkey sausage, egg, and cheese croissant and it was $9.50 each.  Had we had bacon (we don't eat pork) our sandwiches would have been $5.65.    The avocado toast was pretty good however it was soggy and may have had a bit too much butter.  It wasn't bad, but yet again.  It was $10.  All in all we paid about $47 for 2 croissant sandwiches, avocado toast, an orange juice, and 2 coffees.   When visiting here you are obviously paying for the location.  Our order probably should. Have been $30 tops.

3.  The service was really good.  They take your order when you arrive and you seat yourself.  However, a waitress will bring out your food and drinks and check in on you occasionally.  Our waitress was friendly and did a good job of making sure we were happy.

4.  The dining area is cozy with a few high top tables.  There are live plants and overall really relaxed vibe.  The downfall is the space can fill up very quickly.  If 5 or 6 orders come in back to back the place will fill up very quickly.  When we visited it was rainy but they do have quite a bit of outdoor seating.  They also provide free WiFi.

4. The parking is horrible! Street parking seems to be the best option.  There is a parking deck across the street but I'm not sure if that deck is public parking.

Food is good here, but I was disappointed with the way they treated me and my golden retriever.  There are no servers to sit you outside, you get a number after you order FROM A COUNTER and go find a spot, which would make anyone think its first come first serve. Also, keep in mind, I did see a small sign on the door about not bringing dogs inside (other than this, no other signs insight), so I do the natural thing and tie her up to the open table outside I plan to sit at.  When I did this and went inside to order, some couple tried to go over to that table to sit and looked like they saw a ghost when they saw the table they "planned to sit at" was taken by a golden retriever...

One of the workers saw this disheveled couple, knew that it was my dog cause she watched me do it, came over to me in line and got upset with me and started claiming they have "signs EVERYWHERE" (ref. the 3rd sentence) stating it not being first come first serve... When I denied seeing any sign anywhere stating that, I responded with "this is a coffee shop, what do you mean I can't tie my dog up outside then order from the COUNTER inside", she followed up with "You don't have to eat here" so I took her up on that suggestion and left.

The tone and handling of the situation were unnecessary and left a very negative impression. It's unfortunate, because the setting and food are otherwise enjoyable. I hope the management considers providing clearer signage and a more respectful approach to customer service in the future.

MOLDY FOOD

My son and I visited ROOTS today for the first time. We ordered breakfast sandwiches, grits, and a blueberry muffin from their case. The hot good was tasty, the ambiance lovely, and overall good atmosphere.

However, the muffin we received was molded. We took it to go and didn't notice it until later. My son took a bite of the muffin he complained he didn't like it and tasted funny. Upon examining it I found mold spots all on the inside of it....

I really wanted to like this spot, however this was disappointing.

Very nice neighborhood cafe.

1.  The coffee is  reasonably priced and taste great.  My wife ordered a latte and enjoyed it so much she grabbed another to take home.

2.  The breakfast sandwiches taste great but are a little overpriced.  We ordered turkey sausage, egg, and cheese croissant and it was $9.50 each.  Had we had bacon (we don't eat pork) our sandwiches would have been $5.65.    The avocado toast was pretty good however it was soggy and may have had a bit too much butter.  It wasn't bad, but yet again.  It was $10.  All in all we paid about $47 for 2 croissant sandwiches, avocado toast, an orange juice, and 2 coffees.   When visiting here you are obviously paying for the location.  Our order probably should. Have been $30 tops.

3.  The service was really good.  They take your order when you arrive and you seat yourself.  However, a waitress will bring out your food and drinks and check in on you occasionally.  Our waitress was friendly and did a good job of making sure we were happy.

4.  The dining area is cozy with a few high top tables.  There are live plants and overall really relaxed vibe.  The downfall is the space can fill up very quickly.  If 5 or 6 orders come in back to back the place will fill up very quickly.  When we visited it was rainy but they do have quite a bit of outdoor seating.  They also provide free WiFi.

4. The parking is horrible! Street parking seems to be the best option.  There is a parking deck across the street but I'm not sure if that deck is public parking.
